comments.body:
So, I had a look at this and this is sort of working as expected, kinda.

`SKImage.FromEncodedData` technically creates a raster image, but a "lazy" raster. You can check this using the `IsLazyGenerated` property. So, when you do `ToRasterImage`, you are actually just getting the same image - which has no pixmap because it probably hasn't read the actual pixels yet.

Now, how do we do what you want to do? Basically, copy the image to a new image:

```csharp
// original
var image = SKImage.FromEncodedData(path);

// create a new image
using var copy = SKImage.Create(new SKImageInfo(image.Width, image.Height));
using var pix = copy.PeekPixels();

// copy the image
image.ReadPixels(pix, 0, 0);
```

This _will work_. But it is code - and we are developers. Developers are known to hate code (it contains bugs). So I just exposed a new overload that does all this for you in #1126:

```csharp
using var image = SKImage.FromEncodedData(path);
using var rasterImage = image.ToRasterImage(preserveLazy: false);
```

After all this, remember we are _copying_ the image. If for some reason you want to modify the pixels, then this is how you do it. But, if you are trying to just _use_ the image, then maybe have a look at the `Subset` members or draw using shaders, color filters or other blend modes. This way, you do not have to allocate or move memory around.
